<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
Three Sachems: Clay, Webster, Calhoun
---
By David Shribman</HL>
<DD> 11/09/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   Three decades ago, <PERSON>John Kennedy</PERSON>, obsessed with greatness in <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> but unwilling to achieve it himself, headed a committee to select which senators to honor with portraits in the ornate Senate Reception Room. 
Scholars and commentators were consulted and the verdict was fairly predictable. 
The top three finishers were <PERSON>Henry Clay</PERSON>, <PERSON>Daniel Webster</PERSON> and <PERSON>John C. Calhoun</PERSON>. 

   Clay, <PERSON>Webster</PERSON> and <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON> -- their names flow off the tongue in a group. 

   The leading political figures of the "second generation" of American leaders, they were, as <ORGANIZATION>University of Virginia</ORGANIZATION> historian <PERSON>Merrill Peterson</PERSON> puts it, "part of the furniture of American memory." 

   "The Great Triumvirate" (<ORGANIZATION>Oxford</ORGANIZATION>, 576 pages, <MONEY>$27.95</MONEY>) is an unusual alchemy -- one part history, one part biography -- by a leading American historian who argues that these three men -- one from the <LOCATION>East</LOCATION>, one from the South, one from the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION> -- were the match of the founding generation of Americans: "When the last of this 'second race of giants' passed away in <DATE>1852</DATE>, nothing was left to challenge the sway of the Lilliputians," he writes. 
"The republic lost its glory -- the regalia of great statesmen." 

   <PERSON>Henry Clay</PERSON>, the man <PERSON>John Quincy Adams</PERSON> called "a republican of the first fire," elevated the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> to new importance. 
He fashioned his own ideology, an "American System" that consisted of policies to encourage national economic development, chiefly protective tariffs and a series of internal improvements that now would be known as public-works projects. 
And though he thought slavery would wither away -- he later advocated repatriating slaves back to <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> as colonists -- he became known for his ability to sculpt compromise after compromise on the slavery question. 
Clay, according to <PERSON>Mr. Peterson</PERSON>, had a "genius for accommodation, sensitivity to opposing political forces and ingenuity in adapting old policies to new conditions." 

   Webster is known in history much the same way he was known as a young <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION> lawyer with a gift for oratory -- the "guardian of the Constitution." 
<PERSON>Mr. Peterson</PERSON> credits him with pioneering the "theory of the Constitution as the fundamental law of one people, rather than a compact of sovereign states." 

   And <PERSON>John C. Calhoun</PERSON>. 
First pressed by the early Nullifiers, then their champion, he embraced this tool of expedience to assure his base in <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION>, to protect his region from the threat of high tariffs and to muffle the drumbeats of Abolition. 
"It took possession of him, transfixed his political vision, and justified all his actions," says <PERSON>Mr. Peterson</PERSON>. 

   He once viewed slavery as scaffolding for the South, support that would be removed "when the building is finished." 
Later he came to call it "a great good." 
He was, moreover, a proponent of small government in the <LOCATION>Jefferson</LOCATION> model, aiming for nothing less, as he put it, "than to turn back the <ORGANIZATION>Government</ORGANIZATION> to where it commences operations in <DATE>1789</DATE>." 
<PERSON>Mr. Peterson</PERSON> sees <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>'s power resting "not on charisma or organization but on a political ideology that postulated unity in the state and eventually in the section as the only means of securing slavery and the South from an encroaching northern majority." 

   The three united in <DATE>1832</DATE> to oppose <PERSON>Andrew Jackson</PERSON> but, <PERSON>Mr. Peterson</PERSON> points out, spent most of their public lives dancing a political version of the country reel, changing partners and calculating their every move with an eye on what the others would do. 
Webster first opposed Clay on tariff protection, then switched sides and found himself opposing <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>. 
<PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>, as vice president under <PERSON>John Quincy Adams</PERSON>, stacked the <ORGANIZATION>Senate Foreign Relations Committee</ORGANIZATION> against <ORGANIZATION>Secretary of State Clay</ORGANIZATION>. 
And although Clay and <PERSON>Webster</PERSON>, the two leading Whigs, united in opposing an independent <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> scheme proffered by the <PERSON>Van Buren</PERSON> administration, they fought so much they paved the way for <PERSON>William Henry Harrison</PERSON> to snatch the presidency in <DATE>1840</DATE>. 

   Each had great achievements. 
From his position in the border state of <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION>, Clay formed two great compromises. 
Although he never shed the charges of "bargain and corruption" growing out of his maneuvers that left <PERSON>John Quincy Adams</PERSON> as president in <DATE>1824</DATE>, he was an active and successful secretary of state. 
Webster is now regarded as among the greatest secretaries of state in history, having prevented war with the British and helped fix the nation's northern border. 
And <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON> today is regarded as one of the few original thinkers of the era that followed the Founding Fathers'. 

   Despite the triumvirs' documented greatness, <PERSON>Mr. Peterson</PERSON> offers harsh assessments of their legacies. 
The Civil War that followed their deaths would have offered Clay "grim proofs of the limits of compromise." 
It would have demonstrated to <PERSON>Webster</PERSON> "the fragility of law and constitutions before moral and social forces he never truly understood." 
And it offered an "awful judgment" on <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>. 
His face ended up on the currency and postage stamps not of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, but of the Confederacy. 

   ---
   <PERSON>Mr. Shribman</PERSON> is a reporter in the Journal's <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> bureau. 

</TEXT>
