<HEAD>Senate Celebrates Its First Two Centuries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>, told it ``is a guardian of
tradition without becoming a barrier to change,'' celebrated its
first two centuries of history on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, recalling its faltering
beginnings and noting its many milestones.
   <DATE>April 6, 1789</DATE>, was the date that the first <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>, meeting in
<LOCATION>New York City</LOCATION>, finally reached a quorum _ and thus was able to
start conducting business _ after a frustrating month of failing to
do so.
   ``History oozes from these walls,'' said <PERSON>Sen. John Glenn</PERSON>,
<LOCATION>D-Ohio</LOCATION>, as the day of commemoration began in the Old Senate Chamber
in the Capitol with the issuing of a postage stamp displaying the
gilt shield and eagle still suspended over the presiding officer's
chair.
   The eagle and shield were there during speeches on the old
chamber's floor which served the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> from <DATE>1810</DATE> to <DATE>1859</DATE>, and can
be seen in <DATE>19th century</DATE> prints involving three famous senators of
the era: <PERSON>Daniel Webster</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Henry Clay</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION>
and <PERSON>John C. Calhoun</PERSON> of <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION>.
   Those three senators and the roles they played in the period
before the Civil War were invoked repeatedly as past and former
senators hailed the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> as an institution.
   <PERSON>Howard H. Baker Jr.</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION>, a former <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> Republican
leader, said the sense of history in the old <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> hall, and in
the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>'s present chamber first occupied in <DATE>1859</DATE>, is so strong
that at times one can truly ``smell the marble.''
   Nearly 20 former senators _ including <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> and former
Democratic leader <PERSON>Mike Mansfield</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION> _ joined senators in
the current 101st <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> for the ceremonies. Members of the <ORGANIZATION>House
of Representatives</ORGANIZATION> celebrated the quorum bicentennial session of
that body on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   Former <PERSON>Sen. Thomas F. Eagleton</PERSON>, a Democrat from <LOCATION>Missouri</LOCATION>, said
that the legacy of the early <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> is the art of the American
political compromise.
   ``Today compromise is woven into constitutional fabric of the
nation,'' <PERSON>Eagleton</PERSON> said.
   Although many senators past and present have regarded compromise
as morally wrong, <PERSON>Eagleton</PERSON> said it is politically essential.
   ``Compromise, in my judgment, is getting a bad rap,'' <PERSON>Eagleton</PERSON>
said. ``Without it we screech to a halt, paralyzed by
intransigence.''
   The <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> session began at <TIME>11 a.m.</TIME>, the hour of the first
session two centuries ago.
   With the conclusion of the ceremony's first half in the old
chamber, senators formed a procession to the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>'s present
meeting place down the hall.
   Senior senators from the states answered the roll call,
beginning with <LOCATION>Delaware</LOCATION>, which became the first state in <DATE>1787</DATE>, and
continuing to <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>, which in <DATE>1959</DATE> became the 50th to join the
union.
   When <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION>'s name was called, Republican <PERSON>Strom Thurmond</PERSON>
gave this response: ``<LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION> was not the first state to be
admitted, but it was the first to secede'' in <DATE>1860</DATE>. After the Civil
War, <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION> returned to the union in <DATE>1868</DATE>.
   Sen. <PERSON>Ted Stevens</PERSON>, <LOCATION>R-Alaska</LOCATION>, noted <PERSON>Thomas Jefferson</PERSON>'s description
of the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> as a stage, and recalled some of the drama the
present chamber has witnessed, including the one-vote defeat of the
attempt to oust President <PERSON>Andrew Johnson</PERSON> during Reconstruction
after the Civil War, and the rejection of President <PERSON>Woodrow
Wilson</PERSON>'s effort to bring the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> into the <ORGANIZATION>League of
Nations</ORGANIZATION> after World War I.
   <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON>George Mitchell</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Maine</LOCATION>, said that while
the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> has undergone many changes over the years, it remains a
place where the rights of the minority are protected and speech can
remain virtually unlimited.
   ``It is a guardian of tradition without becoming a barrier to
change,'' he said.
   Senators moved in and out of the ceremonies to spirited <PERSON>John
Philip Sousa</PERSON> marches played by the <ORGANIZATION>Marine Corps</ORGANIZATION> band.
   A tourist asked a doorman: ``Does a band play every day the
<ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> meets?''
   ``No,'' the doorman replied. ``Only once every 200 years.''
</TEXT>
