<HL> Letters to the Editor:
Assessing Early American Tariffs</HL>
<DD> 08/18/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   It was amusing to read <PERSON>James Bovard</PERSON>'s "American History: Pass a Tariff, Start a War" (editorial page, <DATE>July 20</DATE>) in defense of free trade, because the truth about American history is that for the greater part of it, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> was a strongly protectionist nation. 
From <DATE>1789</DATE> until the end of World War II, our country rose to become the greatest economic power on earth behind high tariff walls. 
The Japanese and <LOCATION>Koreans</LOCATION> seem to have learned more from American history than we have. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Bovard</PERSON> cites anachronisms such as <PERSON>John Taylor</PERSON> and nonentities such as <PERSON>Frank H. Hurd</PERSON>. 
But those of us who believe a little trade regulation might be a very good thing indeed can take comfort in such historical allies as <PERSON>Alexander Hamilton</PERSON>, <PERSON>Henry Clay</PERSON>, <PERSON>Daniel Webster</PERSON> and <PERSON>John C. Calhoun</PERSON> before he became the sectional spokesman for the free-trading but slave-holding plantation owners of the south. 

   What is more, since <PERSON>George</PERSON> <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Thomas Jefferson</PERSON>, <PERSON>Abraham Lincoln</PERSON> and <PERSON>Theodore Roosevelt</PERSON> all supported tariffs or other protectionist measures during their presidencies, we might even want to conclude that the world's greatest monument to fair trade was carved in the rock of <LOCATION>Mount Rushmore</LOCATION>. 

   Barry Gewen
   <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>
   ---
   <PERSON>Mr. Bovard</PERSON> makes the bold claim that "Few people realize that restrictive trade policies were a major cause of the American Revolution." 
He cites <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s prohibiting Americans from "erecting any mill for rolling or slitting iron." 

   Americans during that time did not seem disturbed by this prohibition. 
<PERSON>John Adams</PERSON> wrote that, "<LOCATION>America</LOCATION> has all along consented, still consent and ever will consent, that Parliament . . . should regulate the trade of the dominions." 
And the <ORGANIZATION>First Continental Congress</ORGANIZATION>, in a resolution, declared that "we cheerfully consent to the operation of such Acts of the British Parliament, as are bona fide restrained to the regulation of our external commerce, for the purpose of securing the commercial advantages of the whole empire to the mother country, and the commercial benefits of its respective members." 

   Pre-Revolutionary Americans perhaps can be excused for thinking that trade restrictions benefit the nation. 
After all, <PERSON>Adam Smith</PERSON>'s "Wealth of Nations" had not yet been published. 
Modern Americans cannot likewise be excused. 

   Prof. <ORGANIZATION>William Irvine
   Wright State University
   Dayton</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>
</TEXT>
