<SECOND>AM-Marshals' Bicentennial,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmen Celebrate 200 Years In Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the days President <PERSON>George Washington</PERSON>
dispatched the first <LOCATION>United States Marshals</LOCATION> to quell the <ORGANIZATION>Whiskey
Rebellion</ORGANIZATION>, the storied lawmen have been part of the country's most
colorful and most violent episodes.
   They did the hanging for famous ``Hanging Judge'' <PERSON>Isaac Parker</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Fort Smith</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ark.</LOCATION>, after rounding up bank and train robbers hiding in
the brush of Indian Territory, smashed whiskey stills during
Prohibition and protected slaves freed after the Civil War.
   The nation's oldest law enforcement organization, the Marshals
began their bicentennial celebration <DATE>Thursday</DATE> with the opening of an
exhibit at the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> followed by a black-tie dinner at a
nearby hotel.
   Organized by the <ORGANIZATION>Marshals Service</ORGANIZATION> with the help of the
<ORGANIZATION>Smithsonian Insitution</ORGANIZATION>, the exhibit displays artifacts from
massacres and shootouts that have earned the men their place in the
lore of the <LOCATION>Wild West</LOCATION> and their immortalization by movie legends
<PERSON>John Wayne</PERSON> and <PERSON>Henry Fonda</PERSON>.
   ``As the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> expanded across the continent, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
Marshals and their deputies established the federal goverment's
authority over areas that had known little order and no goverment.
Most of them were rough, uncouth men,'' according to an excerpt of
the Marshals' official history by <PERSON>Frederick S. Calhoun</PERSON>.
   The brothers of Deputy <PERSON>Frank Dalton</PERSON>, one of many men killed in
Indian Territory, were also deputies before they turned to robbing
banks.
   ``They were the federal goverment at the local level,'' <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>
said. ``There was no infrastructure of a bureaucracy, so when the
citizens got mad they took it out on the federal marshals.''
   As a result, as many as 100 marshals and their deputies died in
Indian Territory between <DATE>1872</DATE> and <DATE>1896</DATE>, their deadliest era, <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>
said.
   ``With the exception of Indian Territory, the far most dangerous
time to be a marshal was in the South after the Civil War,'' <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>
said. ``If the <PERSON>Ku Klux Klan</PERSON> didn't get you, the moonshiners did.''
   At least 400 and as many as 700 marshals have died in the line of
duty, more than any other law enforcement agency. But the exact
number isn't known because of difficulties in determining whether
members of posses had actually been deputized before their deaths,
said <ORGANIZATION>Marshals Service</ORGANIZATION> director <ORGANIZATION>Stanley Morris</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``At almost every point in history when the federal government
was involved in a significant event, there were marshals
participating,'' said <ORGANIZATION>Marshals Service</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Stephen Boyle</PERSON>.
   A marshal who fired the gun that sent settlers scrambling for a
homestead in the <LOCATION>Oklahoma</LOCATION> land run of <DATE>1889</DATE> at <LOCATION>Guthrie</LOCATION>; marshals
guarded the first black student at the <ORGANIZATION>University of
Mississippi-Oxford</ORGANIZATION> in the <DATE>1960s</DATE>; and marshals ringed the <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION>
during the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> war protests of the early <DATE>1970s</DATE>.
   They arrested gangster <PERSON>Al Capone</PERSON> twice and took the census until
<DATE>1880</DATE>.
   As evidence of those events, the Marshals' exhibit contains the
arrest warrant for Geronimo, an <DATE>1870</DATE> <PERSON>Ku Klux Klan</PERSON> robe and hood from
a recruit in the Klan's birthpace of <LOCATION>Pulaski</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tenn.</LOCATION>, a <DATE>1790</DATE> whiskey
still from the Whiskey Rebellion era, and one of the two machine
guns from the <ORGANIZATION>St. Valentine</ORGANIZATION>'s Day massacre in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> _ the
bloodiest of Prohibition.
   The exhibit, which will tour a dozen cities over the next 2{
years, also includes a <PERSON>Jesse James</PERSON> vest and sidearm, and original
drawings by <PERSON>Wyatt Earp</PERSON> of four gunfights, including one at the OK
Corral involving the legendary wild West marshal.
   Appointed by the president, the 94 district <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> marshals are a
part of the executive branch, created by the first <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> in the
Judiciary Act of <DATE>1789</DATE> _ the same law that established the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme
Court</ORGANIZATION> and the federal judicial system.
   The marshals of the <DATE>1980s</DATE> provide security in federal court and
protect <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> justices when they travel beyond <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
They operate the witness protection program that gives new
identities to those whose lives are jeopardized by testifying for
the government, and track down federal fugitives.
   They also take custody of those accused of federal crimes and
transport federal prisoners, running the government's only scheduled
airline service with two <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> 727s and smaller aircraft out of
their <LOCATION>Oklahoma City</LOCATION> hub, <PERSON>Morris</PERSON> said.
   They are responsible for property seized in the war on drugs and
other federal crimes and have managed horse ranches, restaurants,
condominums, a golf course and a greenhouse.
   With just 3,000 employees, the service is smaller than the <ORGANIZATION>New
York City Police Department</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Morris</PERSON> said, yet its ranks are
stationed in every <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> judicial district from <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> to the <LOCATION>Virgin
Islands</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
