<HEAD>Historic Spa Foundering in Red Ink</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD SPRINGS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly two centuries, society's
highest and mightiest flocked to this <LOCATION>Allegheny Mountain</LOCATION> resort to
sip the natural mineral water and soak up elegance at one of
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s oldest spas.
   But the <ORGANIZATION>Bedford Springs Hotel</ORGANIZATION> is foundering these days as its
owners struggle to repay debts and avoid the auction block.
   ``We have the ability to revive something historic and to spur
the economy, and that should sound like government funding would be
available to do that,'' said <PERSON>Hobert Hobbs</PERSON>, 50, vice president of <ORGANIZATION>Sky
Group International Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, which owns the hotel.
   Unless an investor comes to the rescue, the resort will be
auctioned off <DATE>Sept. 21</DATE>, nine days before <MONEY>$4.8 million</MONEY> is due the
bank. The money is what was spent from a <MONEY>$7.5 million</MONEY> loan made in
<DATE>1987</DATE> for renovations that weren't completed because of a dispute
between owners that ended up in bankruptcy court.
   Local folks fear that a new owner will raze the 185-year-old
hotel or modernize it to the point that all ambience is lost.
   Merchants in neighboring <LOCATION>Bedford</LOCATION>, a town of about 4,000 people
brimming with antique and art shops, say business already is off <PERCENT>20
percent</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>25 percent</PERCENT> as a result of the hotel turmoil. Tourism
accounts for about a third of the area's income, according to <PERSON>Joe
Lurie</PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION>Bedford County Office of Economic
Development</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``It's like losing a big industry,'' he said.
   A few years ago, nearly 200 people worked at <ORGANIZATION>Bedford Springs
Hotel</ORGANIZATION>, a stately stretch of three- and four-story buildings on 2,300
acres in south-central <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION>. They tended an 18-hole golf
course, tennis courts, a stocked lake, and hiking and riding trails
during the May-through-October season.
   Forty-seven employees are left. All but 66 of the hotel's 244
rooms are closed to guests, who dine at the golf clubhouse because
the main kitchen is shut down.
   Eight guest rooms were occupied on a recent weeknight, leaving
doorman <PERSON>Joe Koontz</PERSON> with little to do except read.
   ``They (guests) ask me what's going to happen next. Well I don't
know what's going to happen next,'' said <PERSON>Koontz</PERSON>, 61.
   <ORGANIZATION>Bedford Springs Hotel</ORGANIZATION>'s troubles, in part, reflect those of the
entire industry, according to industry observers.
   ``The hotel industry is in deep trouble all around the country,
big time. There are <PERCENT>45 percent</PERCENT> more rooms than demand in the whole
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. It's an overbuilt industry,'' said <PERSON>Phil Goodman</PERSON>,
president of <ORGANIZATION>Western Media Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, a marketing company in <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Edward Watkins</PERSON>, editor of Lodging Hospitality, a monthly trade
magazine, estimates about 50 of the nation's 45,000 hotels and
motels are ``old-line resorts,'' which offer traditional types of
recreation in a spread-out, rural setting with a meal plan. Only a
dozen or so are 100 years old or more.
   ``The traditional guest they served is getting old and dying
off,'' he said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Bedford Springs Hotel</ORGANIZATION> was opened in <DATE>1804</DATE> by a doctor drawn by
the area's magnesia springs and their reputed curative powers. The
springs had been used for centuries before by Indians.
   The spa quickly attracted the notables of the times: <PERSON>Mrs. John
Quincy Adams</PERSON> and her daughters, <PERSON>Aaron Burr</PERSON>, and statesmen <PERSON>Henry
Clay</PERSON>, <PERSON>John C. Calhoun</PERSON> and <PERSON>Daniel Webster</PERSON>.
   President <PERSON>James Polk</PERSON> visited in <DATE>1848</DATE> followed by five other
presidents, including <PERSON>James Buchanan</PERSON>, who used the spa as a <DATE>summer</DATE>
<ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION>. Candidate <PERSON>Ronald Reagan</PERSON> stayed overnight in <DATE>1974</DATE>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> met at the resort to decide a case in
<DATE>1855</DATE>, the only time it ever met outside its chambers. And it was
there in <DATE>1858</DATE> that <PERSON>Buchanan</PERSON> received the first Trans-Atlantic cable,
a message from <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>'s Queen Victoria.
   During World War II, the <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> established a radio training school
at the resort. The hotel also housed Japanese diplomats.
   <LOCATION>Bedford Springs</LOCATION> is being considered, along with <ORGANIZATION>State College</ORGANIZATION>, as
a possible <DATE>summer</DATE> home for the <ORGANIZATION>Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra</ORGANIZATION>.
   Hobbs and community leaders hope the orchestra's interest will
prompt the bank to grant a delay on payment of the loan.
   ``We're still confident something good is going to happen,''
<PERSON>Hobbs</PERSON> said. ``Was it <PERSON>Yogi Berra</PERSON> who said, `It ain't over til it's
over?' Well it ain't over til it's over.'''
</TEXT>
