<HEAD>Charles Wiltse, Historian of 19th Century Americans, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Charles Wiltse</PERSON>, a historian who was
considered a leading biographical expert on <DATE>19th century America</DATE>,
has died at the age of 83.
   <PERSON>Wiltse</PERSON> died <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> at the <ORGANIZATION>Dartmouth-Hitchcock Clinic</ORGANIZATION> after
suffering a heart attack, said <PERSON>John Wilson</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Rand-Wilson Funeral
Home</ORGANIZATION>.
   Wiltse edited the papers of <PERSON>Daniel Webster</PERSON>, the prominent
congressman and secretary of state, in a 16-volume work completed
last year. He also was an expert on one of <PERSON>Webster</PERSON>'s
contemporaries, statesman and Vice President <PERSON>John Calhoun</PERSON>. In the
<DATE>1940s</DATE> he prepared a three-volume set on <ORGANIZATION>Calhoun</ORGANIZATION>'s papers.
   He was the author of ``The Jeffersonian Tradition in American
Democracy'' and ``The New Nation 1800-1845,'' as well as many
articles on the history of the period.
   He was a professor of history at <ORGANIZATION>Dartmouth College</ORGANIZATION> from <DATE>1966</DATE> to
<DATE>1972</DATE>, before retiring from teaching.
   <PERSON>Wiltse</PERSON> was born in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, and was a <DATE>1929</DATE> graduate of
<ORGANIZATION>West Virginia University</ORGANIZATION>. He earned a Ph.D. at <ORGANIZATION>Cornell University</ORGANIZATION>
in <DATE>1932</DATE>.
   He is survived by a sister, <PERSON>Clara Wiltse</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Muncie</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ind</LOCATION>. His
wife died in <DATE>1985</DATE>.
</TEXT>
