<HEAD>Court Upholds IRS Ruling Denying Tax Exempt Status to All-White
School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Tax Court</ORGANIZATION> has upheld an <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> order
denying a tax exemption to a <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION> private school on
grounds it discriminates against blacks.
   ``The absence of either a single black student in the school or
a plausible explanation of inability to attract black students
permits an inference of discrimination, particularly in view of ...
(the school's) history,'' the court held.
   The decision, made public <DATE>Monday</DATE>, means that contributions to
<ORGANIZATION>Calhoun Academy</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>St. Matthews</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>S.C.</LOCATION>, are not deductible.
   Chief <PERSON>Judge Arthur L. Nims III</PERSON> held that although <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON> had
adopted a racially non-discriminatory policy, the school had failed
to operate under that policy.
   ``We cannot conclude that non-discrimination in ... operations
is more likely than discrimination,'' <PERSON>Nims</PERSON> wrote for the court.
   <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>, organized as a not-for-profit corporation <DATE>Dec. 30,
1969</DATE>, offers classes for grades kindergarten through 12. The school
has never had a black pupil or teacher. Two black parents requested
and were given application forms for enrollment in <DATE>1984-85</DATE>, but a
black teacher has never applied for employment.
   Since <DATE>1982</DATE>, at least one pupil of Oriental background has been
enrolled in <LOCATION>Calhoun</LOCATION>. The only non-white teacher, a
Japanese-American, was hired in <DATE>1983</DATE>, court records showed.
   The school amended its charter in <DATE>1985</DATE> and began advertising
that it did not discriminate. It applied to the <ORGANIZATION>Internal Revenue
Service</ORGANIZATION> for a tax exemption in <DATE>1986</DATE>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> denied the exemption, citing the fact that <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON> was
formed at a time of enforced desegregation in area public schools,
its total lack of black pupils despite blacks being a majority in
<LOCATION>Calhoun County</LOCATION> and its failure to announce a policy of
non-discrimination until <DATE>1985</DATE>.
   At a later meeting, the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> suggested that <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON> improve its
contacts with the black community and offer reduced tuition for
black pupils. A director of the school rejected the reduced-tuition
suggestion, saying it would result in unequal treatment on the
basis of race.
   In siding with the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Tax Court</ORGANIZATION> cited a <DATE>1983</DATE> case in which
the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> had stripped a tax exemption from <ORGANIZATION>Bob Jones
University</ORGANIZATION> after finding that it discriminated on the basis of race.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> held that racially discriminatory schools
violate fundamental public policy and cannot be viewed as
conferring a benefit on the public.
   ``From the record before us,'' <PERSON>Nims</PERSON> wrote, ``it appears that
white students and their parents gravitate to petitioner (<PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>)
at least in part because of a historical absence of black students:
Petitioner admits that the local public schools are superior in
material respects, yet considerably less expensive.
   ``Petitioner's survival would thus depend to some extent on
perpetuating its history,'' the court ruled, adding that such
discrimination would clearly preclude a federal tax exemption.
</TEXT>
