private property.
   Instead, he obtained a statement from two lawyers who said they
had examined the letters and found nothing relevant to the
investigation.
   The uproar continued and <PERSON>Blaine</PERSON> set about to defuse it.
   On <DATE>June 5</DATE> he appeared on the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> floor and waved the packet
exclaiming, ``There they are. ... There are the original letters.''
   Blaine then read aloud what he said were the contents of each of
the letters. He said he had handed over ``every solitary scrap and
scrimption'' for inclusion in the <ORGANIZATION>Congressional Record</ORGANIZATION>.
   They had, he declared, ``no more to do with that investigation
than the <LOCATION>North Pole</LOCATION>.''
   But no one was ever shown the originals of the letters to verify
<PERSON>Blaine</PERSON>'s reading of them.
   Events moved rapidly.
   Blaine collapsed outside his church suffering from a possible
heat stroke. The investigation was postponed for two weeks to await
his recovery. But before the committee could reconvene, the
governor of <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> appointed <PERSON>Blaine</PERSON> to fill a vacancy in the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>.
   The investigation was postponed again, and eventually died.
   Blaine's political backers proceeded, in classical <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>
fashion, to make the best of a bad situation.
   In the <DATE>20th century</DATE> it's called making lemonade out of a lemon.
   Blaine's name was placed in nomination at the <ORGANIZATION>Republican
National Convention</ORGANIZATION> by <PERSON>Robert G. Ingersoll</PERSON> on <DATE>June 15, 1876</DATE>, with
words that gave <PERSON>Blaine</PERSON> an enduring nickname: ``The plumed knight
from the state of <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION>.''
   ``Like an armed warrior, like a plumed knight, <PERSON>James G. Blaine</PERSON>
marched down the halls of the <ORGANIZATION>American Congress</ORGANIZATION> and threw his
shining lance full and fair against the brazen forehead of every
traitor to his country and every maligner of his fair reputation.''
   Blaine never obtained the presidency.
   But he twice was appointed secretary of state.
   No <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> speaker has ever been ousted. But several have been
singed during the 200-year history of <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Henry Clay</PERSON>, who was elected speaker six times, drew accusations
of ``corrupt bargain'' when the close election of <DATE>1824</DATE> was thrown
into the <ORGANIZATION>House of Representatives</ORGANIZATION>.
   The choice was between <PERSON>Andrew Jackson</PERSON> and <PERSON>John Quincy Adams</PERSON>.
Clay and other members of the <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION> delegation tipped the
balance in favor of <ORGANIZATION>Adams</ORGANIZATION>.
   The accusations flew after the victorious <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> named Clay as
his secretary of state.
   Speaker <PERSON>Samuel J. Randall</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> Democrat, promptly
called for his own investigation in <DATE>1879</DATE> after being accused of
favoritism toward a company which provided the paper for the bonds
and banknotes produced by the <ORGANIZATION>Bureau of Engraving</ORGANIZATION>.
   He was quickly cleared.
   In <DATE>1910</DATE> Speaker <PERSON>Joseph G. Cannon</PERSON> faced a rebellion against his
imperious and heavy handed rule of the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>.
   Although not deposed, Cannon was stripped of much of his power.
   Speaker <PERSON>Thomas P.</PERSON> ``Tip'' <PERSON>O'Neill</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Mass.</LOCATION>, was named in the
so-called ``Koreagate'' influence peddling scandal in the <DATE>1970</DATE>'s
but was exonerated.
</TEXT>
