<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Joseph A. Bevilacqua</PERSON>, whose lifelong
friendships with reputed mobsters tarnished and eventually ended his
career as <LOCATION>Rhode Island</LOCATION>'s top legislator and top judge, died
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE>. He was 70.
   <PERSON>Bevilacqua</PERSON> was elected to the <ORGANIZATION>Rhode Island House</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1954</DATE> and
maintained a successful criminal law practice while he rose through
the ranks to become majority leader in <DATE>1966</DATE> and speaker in <DATE>1969</DATE>.
   Questions about his ties to criminals came into the open when the
<ORGANIZATION>General Assembly</ORGANIZATION> elected him chief justice of the state <ORGANIZATION>Supreme
Court</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1976</DATE>. Investigations were conducted, and in <DATE>1985</DATE> Bevilacqua
was censured by the <ORGANIZATION>Commission on Judicial Tenure</ORGANIZATION> and Discipline for
associating with known criminals. In <DATE>1986</DATE>, after the <ORGANIZATION>General
Assembly</ORGANIZATION> launched impeachment proceedings, <PERSON>Bevilacqua</PERSON> resigned.
</TEXT>
