<TEXT>
<P>
Priscilla Presley plays "Girl <DATE>Friday</DATE>" to detective <PERSON>Andrew Dice Clay</PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION>Fox</ORGANIZATION>'s 
"Ford Fairlane," filming locally next month. Look for romantic sparks along 
with dictation in the off-beat murder mystery from director <PERSON>Renny Harlin</PERSON> and 
producer <PERSON>Joel Silver</PERSON>. . . . 
</P>
<P>
<PERSON>Julia Roberts</PERSON> is an <LOCATION>L.A.</LOCATION> street prostitute set up in a plush suite by a 
visiting business acquisitor in <LOCATION>Touchstone</LOCATION>'s "3000," which films in <DATE>June</DATE>. 
<PERSON>Steven Reuther</PERSON> and <PERSON>Arnon Milchan</PERSON> produce the dark "Pygmalion-ish" tale written 
by <PERSON>John Lawton</PERSON> and <PERSON>Stephen Metcalfe</PERSON>. <PERSON>Gary Marshall</PERSON> directs. . . . 
</P>
<P>
<PERSON>Matthew Modine</PERSON> and <PERSON>Daphne Zuniga</PERSON> have signed up for med school next month in 
<ORGANIZATION>Disney</ORGANIZATION>'s "Gross Anatomy," a comedy in the "Paper Chase" mode. <PERSON>Thom Eberhardt</PERSON> 
directs the screenplay by <PERSON>Mark Spragge</PERSON> and <PERSON>Ron Nyswaner</PERSON>. <PERSON>Howard Rosenman</PERSON> and 
<ORGANIZATION>Debra Hill</ORGANIZATION> produce. . . . 
</P>
<P>
<PERSON>Raul Julia</PERSON> is <PERSON>Dr. Frankenstein</PERSON> in "Frankenstein Unbound," which marks the 
directorial return (a record 18-year hiatus) of <PERSON>Roger Corman</PERSON>. In <PERSON>Corman</PERSON>, <PERSON>Brian 
Aldis</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>F.X. Feeney</ORGANIZATION>'s script, a 21st-Century scientist goes back two 
centuries to discover the literary creation was real. The <ORGANIZATION>Thom Mount Co</ORGANIZATION>. 
production gets underway in <LOCATION>Bergamo</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> in <DATE>June</DATE>. . . . In addition to 
writing-directing "My Father's Eyes," <PERSON>Lou Diamond Phillips</PERSON> now stars in the 
production next <DATE>September</DATE>. Phillips plays a young man -- seen in flashbacks -- 
who dies in a freak accident shortly after the birth of his son, who's now a 
teen-ager. <PERSON>Karen Allen</PERSON> co-stars in the <PERSON>Daniel Eisenberg</PERSON> production. . . . 
</P>
<P>
Rip Torn plays <PERSON>Walt Whitman</PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION>Cinepix</ORGANIZATION>'s "Beautiful Dreamers," a romantic idyll 
filming next month in <LOCATION>Toronto</LOCATION>. Written and directed by <PERSON>John Kent Harris</PERSON>, the 
story centers on the writer's affair with a woman doctor in <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> during the 
<DATE>1880s</DATE>. Colm Feore and <PERSON>Wendel Meldrun</PERSON> co-star in the <PERSON>Steven Roth</PERSON> production. . . 
. 
</P>
<P>
<PERSON>Richard Ford</PERSON>'s novel "Bright Angel" goes to screen this <DATE>summer</DATE> with <PERSON>Dermot 
Mulroney</PERSON> portraying a young man attempting to reconcile with his father. <PERSON>Sam 
Shepard</PERSON> plays the enigmatic dad in <ORGANIZATION>Ford</ORGANIZATION>'s adaptation for director <ORGANIZATION>Michael 
Fields</ORGANIZATION>. Sue <PERSON>Baden-Powell</PERSON>, <PERSON>Page Simpson</PERSON> and <PERSON>Rob MacLean</PERSON> produce for <ORGANIZATION>Hemdale</ORGANIZATION>. . . 
. 
</P>
<P>
Guy <PERSON>Madison</PERSON>, TV's Wild <PERSON>Bill Hickock</PERSON>, and <PERSON>Rory Calhoun</PERSON> play old cowhands in 
Wouk/Ware's "Bad Jim." The shaggy dog western centers on a good guy who goes 
wrong after finding <PERSON>Billy</PERSON> the Kid's horse. <PERSON>John Clark Gable</PERSON> stars for 
writer-director <PERSON>Clyde Ware</PERSON> with filming set outside <LOCATION>Phoenix</LOCATION> next month. . . . 
</P>
<P>
Duet's <ORGANIZATION>Alison La Placa</ORGANIZATION> joins <ORGANIZATION>Orion</ORGANIZATION>'s "Madhouse" as <ORGANIZATION>Kirstie Alley</ORGANIZATION>'s very jealous 
older sister. Also added to the cast are <PERSON>John Diehl</PERSON>, <PERSON>Bradley Gregg</PERSON> and <PERSON>Robert 
Ginty</PERSON>, a befuddled neighbor who sees <PERSON>John Larroquette</PERSON>'s peaceful home life 
crumble as friends and cousins invade. <PERSON>Leslie Dixon</PERSON> produces and <PERSON>Tom Ropelewski</PERSON> 
writes and directs next month in <LOCATION>Tucson</LOCATION>. . . . 
</P>
<P>
<PERSON>Donald Pleasence</PERSON> returns as <PERSON>Dr. Loomis</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Galaxy</LOCATION>'s "Halloween 5: The Revenge of 
<PERSON>Michael Myers</PERSON>," a <DATE>May</DATE> start in <LOCATION>Salt Lake City</LOCATION>. In the new edition actress 
<PERSON>Danielle Harris</PERSON> has empathic responses with the demonic <PERSON>Michael Myers</PERSON>, who's in 
pursuit of <PERSON>Wendy Kaplan</PERSON>. Dominique Othenin-Gerard directs and co-wrote with 
<PERSON>Shem Bitterman</PERSON> and <PERSON>Michael Jacobs</PERSON> for producer Moustapha Akkad. . . . <PERSON>LEONARD 
KLADY</PERSON> 
</P></TEXT>
