<HEAD>Blocks Dropped On I-75 Kill Macon Man, Injure Three Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALHOUN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old man driving on <LOCATION>Interstate 75</LOCATION>
was killed when a cinder block was dropped from an overpass through
his windshield, causing him to lose control and crash.
   His two daughters, ages 9 and 11, were injured, authorities said.
   The <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> night crash, which killed <PERSON>Harold Parker</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Macon</LOCATION>,
followed by a few minutes a similar incident in which a 5-year-old
boy was injured, said <PERSON>Charles Johnson</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Georgia Bureau of
Investigation</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON> office.
   ``We don't know the motive other than just random meanness,'' he
said. ``We're looking at trying to locate who did it.''
   <PERSON>Annette Printup</PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION>Georgia State Patrol</ORGANIZATION> post
in <LOCATION>Calhoun</LOCATION>, said the cinder block shattered the windshield of
<ORGANIZATION>Parker</ORGANIZATION>'s Jeep five miles south of <PERSON>Calhoun</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>LaTonya Parker</PERSON>, 9, was hospitalized in serious condition and
<PERSON>Lamonda Parker</PERSON>, 11, was in stable condition.
</TEXT>
