<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Paul McCartney</PERSON> says rock stars are
singing more about ecological issues because world leaders aren't
doing enough to protect the earth's environment.
   ``Governments _ especially <PERSON>George Bush</PERSON> and <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> _
aren't doing enough work,'' the former <ORGANIZATION>Beatle</ORGANIZATION> said at a news
conference <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   The 47-year-old singer, his wife, <PERSON>Linda</PERSON>, their children and his
band have been in Rio since <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> for two shows expected to
break attendence records.
   <PERSON>Jeff Baker</PERSON>, <PERSON>McCartney</PERSON>'s press spokesman, said 150,000 tickets
were sold for <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s show and all 175,000 tickets were sold for
today's concert at <ORGANIZATION>Rio</ORGANIZATION>'s Maracana soccer stadium, the world's
largest arena. Previously, the largest crowd to watch <PERSON>McCartney</PERSON> in
concert numbered 80,000.
   The Rio shows were to close a 33-city world concert tour. But
<PERSON>McCartney</PERSON> told reporters he was considering proposals to extend the
tour to <LOCATION>Liverpool</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>England</LOCATION> _ the Beatles' hometown _ in <DATE>May</DATE>.
</TEXT>
