<HEAD>Snow In The Southeast - Already?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Brilliantly colored fall foliage was coated with snow and ice
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> in the mountains of <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION> and frost headed as far
south as <LOCATION>Alabama</LOCATION>.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended during the afternoon over
<LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>South Carolina</LOCATION>, northeastern <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION>, eastern
<LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION> and southwestern <LOCATION>Virginia</LOCATION>.
   The rain was mixed with snow in the <LOCATION>Appalachians</LOCATION> and changed
completely to snow at higher elevations.
   ``It was very pretty on these colored leaves,'' said <PERSON>Beulah
Calhoun</PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION>Calhoun Farm Supply</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Newland</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.C.</LOCATION>
   Elsewhere in <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION>, 8 inches of snow accumulated at
<ORGANIZATION>Mount Mitchell</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Mount Pisgah</ORGANIZATION> got a little more than an inch, the
<ORGANIZATION>National Weather Service</ORGANIZATION> reported. The <ORGANIZATION>National Park Service</ORGANIZATION> closed
two sections of the <ORGANIZATION>Blue Ridge Parkway</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION> because of
snow.
   ``I hear there is enough to scrape up a snowball,'' said <PERSON>Hugh
Morton</PERSON> at Grandfather Mountain.
   In eastern <LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION>, snow closed the <ORGANIZATION>Clingman Dome</ORGANIZATION> road in the
<LOCATION>Great Smoky Mountains National Park</LOCATION>, the weather service said.
   At lower elevations in <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION>, thunderstorms produced
locally heavy rain at <LOCATION>Charlotte</LOCATION>, including 1.50 inches in the six
hours up to <TIME>2 p.m. EDT</TIME>, and across much of <LOCATION>Mecklenburg County</LOCATION>,
flooding some streets and roads, the weather service said.
   Hail about an inch in diameter fell at <LOCATION>Locust</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.C.</LOCATION>
   A tornado warning was issued for part of eastern <LOCATION>North Carolina</LOCATION>
after a waterspout was spotted offshore. The waterspout, a tornado
that forms over water, did not come ashore.
   Cold air headed southward across the <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tennessee</LOCATION> valleys
with temperatures expected to reach the low 30s by <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME>
in <LOCATION>northern Alabama</LOCATION>, and the mid to upper 30s across central and
southern <LOCATION>Alabama</LOCATION>.
   Frost advisories were posted over much of <LOCATION>Kentucky</LOCATION> and frost
warnings were issued over southwestern <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>. Advisories for frost
and freezing temperatures were posted over <LOCATION>Indiana</LOCATION> and southeastern
<LOCATION>Lower Michigan</LOCATION>.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered over western <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> state and
northeastern <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>.
   Rain extended from north-central and western <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> state
into northwestern <LOCATION>Oregon</LOCATION>.
   Strong, gusty wind blew across the northern <LOCATION>Pacific Coast</LOCATION> during
the morning, with gusts reaching 44 mph at <LOCATION>Astoria</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ore.</LOCATION>, 47 mph at
<LOCATION>Bellingham</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Wash.</LOCATION>, and 56 mph at Seaside, <LOCATION>Ore</LOCATION>.
   <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s low for the Lower 48 states was 19 degrees in
<LOCATION>Gunnison</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Colo</LOCATION>.
   Temperatures around the nation at <TIME>3 p.m. EDT</TIME> ranged from 34
degrees at <LOCATION>Chippewa County Airport</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mich.</LOCATION>, to 96 degrees at <LOCATION>Palm
Springs</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
