<HEAD>Did Abe Lincoln Visit Cape May?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to ADD that Monday is Lincoln's birthday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE MAY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven score and one year ago, the <ORGANIZATION>A.
Lincoln</ORGANIZATION> who visited this seashore town may have been just a grocer
from <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION>.
   But some residents continue to insist it was the future 16th
president who stayed in a hotel in this resort community on <DATE>July
31, 1849</DATE>.
   Those who dispute the tale say Lincoln, whose birthday comes
<DATE>Monday</DATE>, was in <LOCATION>Springfield</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ill.</LOCATION>, practicing law that long-ago <DATE>July
31</DATE>, winning a judgment of <MONEY>$112.30</MONEY> for a client. Casting further
doubt is a record of an <PERSON>Abel Lincoln</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION> grocer who
they say may have headed to the Jersey shore that <DATE>summer</DATE> day.
   ``All these years, we may have been honoring a grocer,'' said
<PERSON>Jake Schaad</PERSON>, who has researched the story and is writing a book
about the history of Cape <DATE>May</DATE>.
   One version of the story claims that, while in <LOCATION>Cape May</LOCATION>, Lincoln
rejected an offer to become governor of the <ORGANIZATION>Oregon Territory</ORGANIZATION> after
his wife, <PERSON>Mary Todd Lincoln</PERSON>, told him she was afraid of Indians,
<PERSON>Schaad</PERSON> said.
   ``It's a good story but it didn't happen,'' <PERSON>Schaad</PERSON> said, adding
that other versions have Lincoln fathering an illegitimate son
while at the shore.
   The town claims to be <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s oldest seashore resort, tracing
its visitors to just after the Revolutionary War, said <PERSON>Jeffrey
Dorwart</PERSON>, a history professor at <ORGANIZATION>Rutgers University-Camden</ORGANIZATION> who is
researching a book for <LOCATION>Cape May County</LOCATION>'s 300th anniversary in <DATE>1992</DATE>.
   Some long-time residents knew <PERSON>Henry Irick</PERSON>, who said that when he
was 16 he came with his father and Lincoln to this community of
Victorian homes and lazy sea breezes.
   <PERSON>Mary Ann Nyblade</PERSON>, a 65-year-old Cape <DATE>May</DATE> resident who can trace
her family in the town back to <DATE>1695</DATE>, said she still clings to
<PERSON>Irick</PERSON>'s story.
   <PERSON>Irick</PERSON> was the son of <PERSON>John S. Irick</PERSON>, a wealthy Vincentown farmer
who supposedly met up with Lincoln and came to the <ORGANIZATION>Mansion House</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Cape May</LOCATION>. He recalled that visit in a newspaper interview in the
late 1890s and the story was born, <PERSON>Ms. Nyblade</PERSON> said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Mansion House</ORGANIZATION> guest register shows an <ORGANIZATION>A. Lincoln</ORGANIZATION> and wife
from <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION> in Room 24. Fire destroyed the hotel in <DATE>1856</DATE> but
the register was saved, <PERSON>Ms. Nyblade</PERSON> said. She acknowledged that the
reference to <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION> on the register was a problem for the
future-president theorists, but say the future president may have
listed <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION> if they had taken the steamboat from there to
<LOCATION>Cape</LOCATION> <DATE>May</DATE>.
   The man who saved that register was <PERSON>Lewis Stevens</PERSON>, and the
250-page book is now in <LOCATION>Huntsville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ala.</LOCATION>, in a safe-deposit box
owned by <PERSON>Bill Stevens</PERSON>, <PERSON>Ms. Nyblade</PERSON>'s nephew and a descendant of
<PERSON>Lewis Stevens</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Bill Stevens</PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the register
contains signatures of other famous people such as <PERSON>Sen. Henry Clay</PERSON>.
However, he said he has learned too much about Lincoln to believe
he could have visited Cape <DATE>May</DATE>.
   ``I'm convinced he was not in <LOCATION>Cape May</LOCATION> at that time,'' he said.
   There's no doubt about that, said <PERSON>Thomas F. Schwartz</PERSON>, curator of
the Lincoln collection at the <ORGANIZATION>Illinois State Historical Library</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Springfield</LOCATION>.
   On <DATE>July 31</DATE>, <PERSON>Lincoln</PERSON> was at least 1,000 miles west of Cape <DATE>May</DATE>,
filing an affidavit in <ORGANIZATION>Sangamon County Circuit Court</ORGANIZATION> for <PERSON>Henry
Bailer</PERSON>, who was owed <MONEY>$111.75</MONEY> by <PERSON>Oliver Davis</PERSON>. Davis ended up paying
<MONEY>$112.30</MONEY>, which <PERSON>Schwartz</PERSON> guesses included interest.
   <PERSON>Dorwart</PERSON> said he can prove President <PERSON>Benjamin Harrison</PERSON> spent
summers in <LOCATION>Cape May</LOCATION>, as did President <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Grant and <PERSON>Woodrow Wilson</PERSON>
while he was governor of <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>. But Lincoln is a different
story.
   ``My sense is that, since looking at the Lincoln papers, he was
in <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Dorwart</PERSON> said.
   He said residents of <LOCATION>Cape May</LOCATION>, 50 miles south of the Mason-Dixon
Line and site of several duels between <ORGANIZATION>Northerners</ORGANIZATION> and Southerners
in the <DATE>1840s</DATE> and <DATE>1850s</DATE>, may have been trying to prove their loyalty
to the <ORGANIZATION>Union</ORGANIZATION> after the Civil War by circulating the story.
   Irick's tale probably cemented the story as fact, <PERSON>Dorwart</PERSON> said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Cape May County Historical Museum</ORGANIZATION> still features a facsimile
of the hotel register signature and everybody acknowledges that
some legends just seem to die hard.
   ``Even if Lincoln didn't come down here, it's part of our
culture that he was here,'' <PERSON>Dorwart</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
